# Entity Framework Migrations And Configuration

Workit uses EF Core with explicit Fluent API configuration. Domain models stay clean; persistence rules belong in configuration classes.

### Configuration Rules

- Use Fluent API configuration classes implementing `IEntityTypeConfiguration<T>`.
- Keep configurations in `Workit.Core/Shared/Persistence/Configurations`.
- Do not use data annotations for persistence mapping.
- Configure every string property with an explicit `HasMaxLength(...)`.
- Configure required fields explicitly with `.IsRequired()` where appropriate.
- Configure indexes and uniqueness explicitly.
- Configure relationships from one side where possible.
- Use `DeleteBehavior.Restrict` for relationships unless cascade delete is an explicit domain requirement.
- Include foreign key properties in domain models when a relationship exists.
- Keep navigation properties nullable unless they are always loaded and required.

Example:

```csharp
public sealed class UserConfiguration : IEntityTypeConfiguration<User>
{
    public void Configure(EntityTypeBuilder<User> builder)
    {
        builder.ToTable("users");
        builder.HasKey(user => user.Id);

        builder.Property(user => user.Email)
            .HasMaxLength(320)
            .IsRequired();

        builder.HasIndex(user => user.Email)
            .IsUnique();

        builder.Property(user => user.PasswordHash)
            .HasMaxLength(256)
            .IsRequired();
    }
}
```

`WorkitDbContextBase` applies configurations from the Core assembly. Any new configuration must be discoverable by `modelBuilder.ApplyConfigurationsFromAssembly(...)`.

### Relationship Rules

One-to-many:

```csharp
builder.HasOne(x => x.Category)
    .WithMany()
    .HasForeignKey(x => x.CategoryId)
    .OnDelete(DeleteBehavior.Restrict);
```

One-to-one:

```csharp
builder.HasOne(x => x.User)
    .WithOne()
    .HasForeignKey<UserProfile>(x => x.UserId)
    .OnDelete(DeleteBehavior.Restrict);
```

Many-to-many relationships should use an explicit join entity when domain behavior, metadata, auditing, or future extensibility is likely.

### Migration Commands

Restore local tools first:

```bash
dotnet tool restore
```

Create migrations:

```bash
dotnet ef migrations add <Name> \
  --project Workit.Core \
  --startup-project Workit.Api \
  --context AppDbContext \
  --output-dir Shared/Persistence/Migrations
```

Apply migrations:

```bash
dotnet ef database update \
  --project Workit.Core \
  --startup-project Workit.Api \
  --context AppDbContext
```

Remove the last unapplied migration:

```bash
dotnet ef migrations remove \
  --project Workit.Core \
  --startup-project Workit.Api \
  --context AppDbContext
```

Rules:

- Use `AppDbContext` for migrations.
- Do not create migrations from `ReadAppDbContext`.
- Use descriptive migration names such as `AddUsersTable` or `AddUserEmailUniqueIndex`.
- Do not hand-edit migration snapshots unless fixing a deliberate EF issue.
- Review generated migrations before committing them.
